2026-04-21 01:30:53 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module cable pair between power supply and control module', 'control module cable pair between control module and load module'] hypothesis_explanation='All internal measurements show that inside the control module the PSU positive node, switch, and red‑LED network are wired correctly. The PSU positive node feeds only the red‑LED/resistor string and the switch; the red‑LED string returns to the control output (−), and there is no internal path from PSU(+) or from the red‑LED string to the control output (+), consistent with the design where the +12 V to the load must arrive *from upstream via the external cable pair*. The continuity tests showed an open circuit from PSU(+) to control output(+), but this is now clearly because those nodes are not supposed to be internally connected — they are linked only externally by the inter‑module cables.\n\nThe constant ~0.36 V seen at the control‑module output(+) and at the load input, along with 0 V at the red LED and no red‑LED illumination, is consistent with the load and red‑LED network being referenced to the same 0 V line while the intended +12 V conductor is never actually present on the control‑module input/output pair. The low voltage is plausibly just leakage or a parasitic path through semiconductors (e.g., the load‑module diode) when the true +12 V conductor is not connected in series through all three modules.\n\nGiven that multiple polarity‑swapping tests were performed but the cabling is entirely unmarked and there are two independent pairs on the control module, the most likely root cause is a persistent cabling/configuration error: the cable pair carrying +12 V from the power supply is not the same physical pair that continues from the control module to the load, so the switch path never ends up in series with the load. In other words, at least one of the external cable pairs is cross‑connected or mis‑mated, so there is no continuous +12 V path from PSU through switch to the load module.\n\nTherefore the suspected fault is in the *module interconnection cabling* between power‑supply↔control and/or control↔load, not in any internal module wiring or components.'
